Maoist guerrillas using dynamite derailedtwo locomotives and four train wagons, interrupting traffic onPeru's sole railway line linking the capital to the centralAndes, where most of the country's mining centres are located,authorities said.    Damages was estimated at 800,000 dlrs in the dynamite blastyesterday at Chacapalca, where the explosion wrecked the trainladen with minerals and 45 metres of the railway line.    Crews hoped to restore traffic to the line later todayafter clearing the damaged train and repairing the tracks atChacapalca, 225 km east of the Capital, Lima.    An official at Mineroperu comercial (Minpeco), Peru's stateminerals marketing firm, said the agency was assessing thesituation. There had not been a declaration of force majeure oncontracts to ship minerals abroad.    Foreign sales of silver, copper, zinc and other mineralsearn Peru over half of its export income. Most of the minerals,extracted and refined in the central peruvian andes, areshipped down the central railway to the lima port of callao. Reuter&#3;